For this challenge, “01001110 01101010 01101011 01100111 01001101 01101010 01000001 01100111 01001110 01111010 01010001 01100111 01001110 01101010 01100111 01100111 01001110 01101010 01101011 01100111 01001110 01101101 01010101 01100111 01001110 01101101 01001001 01100111 01001101 01101010 01000001 01100111 01001110 01111010 01010001 01100111 01001110 01101010 01100111 01100111 01001110 01101010 01000101 01100111 01001110 01111010 01010001 01100111 01001101 01101010 01000001 01100111 01001110 01111010 01001101 01100111 01001110 01101010 01100111 01100111 01001110 01101101 01011001 01100111 01001110 01111010 01010101 01100111 01001110 01101101 01001101 01100111 01001110 01101010 01010001 01100111 01001101 01101010 01000001 01100111 01001110 01101010 01001001 01100111 01001110 01101010 01010101 01100111 01001101 01101010 01000001 01100111 01001110 01101010 01010101 01100111 01001110 01101101 01010101 01100111 01001110 01101101 01011001 01100111 01001110 01111010 01010101 01100111 01001110 01101010 01100011 01100111 01001110 01101010 01100111 01100111 01001101 01101010 01000001 01100111 01001110 01101101 01001101 01100111 01001110 01101010 01000101 01100111 01001110 01111010 01101011 01100111 01001110 01101010 01010101 01100111 01001110 01111010 01001001 01100111 01001110 01111010 01001101 00111101” is the encrypted message
The title, onion, hints that there are multiple layers of ciphers in which this message is decrypted
One simplified way to solve this problem would be to use the website, “CyberChef”, which by using the “magic” command, it allows you to decrypt all of the layers in one go without having to recognize the ciphers used, giving you the final flag: “i think that should be enough layers”
Another way, if you were not aware of the previous method, would be to 
first recognize the cipher as binary, decode that, getting “NjkgMjAgNzQgNjggNjkgNmUgNmIgMjAgNzQgNjggNjEgNzQgMjAgNzMgNjggNmYgNzUgNmMgNjQgMjAgNjIgNjUgMjAgNjUgNmUgNmYgNzUgNjcgNjggMjAgNmMgNjEgNzkgNjUgNzIgNzM=” as your new message, which is in Base64, 
decode it, getting “69 20 74 68 69 6e 6b 20 74 68 61 74 20 73 68 6f 75 6c 64 20 62 65 20 65 6e 6f 75 67 68 20 6c 61 79 65 72 73”, as your new message, which is in Hexadecimal format, 
and finally, decode that, and get “i think that should be enough layers” as the final flag
